    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="308"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d308">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/2479½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 6, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I send you a memorandum<note
                        n="33" xml:id="d308fn1">Not printed; the memorandum bears the notation:
                        “Read to Cabinet by President Mch. 7/16 RL,” and is substantially the same
                        as the telegram of Mar. 9, 1916, to the Ambassadors in Germany and
                        Austria-Hungary, <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_202">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, supp., p.
                        202</ref>.</note> which I have prepared setting forth clearly, I think, the
                    negotiations and conversations which I have had in regard to the matter of armed
                    merchant vessels, and the recent declaration of February 10th by the Teutonic
                    Powers in regard to submarine warfare.<note n="34" xml:id="d308fn2">See telegram
                        No. 3474, Feb. 10, 1916, 10 p. m., from the Ambassador in Germany, <ref
                            target="frus1916Supp#pg_163">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 163</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I suggest, for your consideration, the advisability of reading this memorandum at
                    the Cabinet meeting tomorrow. I feel that the members of the Cabinet ought to
                    know something of the difficulties which we have had to face and particularly
                    the adroit efforts which have been made by the German Ambassador, for I consider
                    Zwiedinek acting more or less under his direction, to cause embarrassment and
                    place this Government in a false light. I assume that when the Ambassador
                    considers the time opportune he will endeavor to show that the recent
                    declaration was instigated by this Government.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
